[2] Russia (Dagestan)
Date: Thu 28 Mar 2013
Source: RIA Dagestan [in Russian, trans., abbreviated Mod.CP, edited]
http://www.riadagestan.ru/news/2013/3/28/153765


According to the Dagestan RIA news agency, the measles epidemic in Dagestan continues undiminished. So far in 2013, a total of 19 laboratory confirmed cases of measles have been recorded in 7 administrative zones. Four of these cases were children under 17 years of age (21.1 percent); 3 were children under one year of age (17.6 percent).

Most of the cases were recorded in the in Tabasaransky and Derbent regions, which accounted for 68 percent of the reported cases in the country. The composition of the cases during the 2013 outbreak by age group is as follows: 70.25 percent (12 persons) aged 20 to 29, 17.6 percent (3 children) under one year of age, while 64 percent of those affected were not employed.

The authorities have responded to the outbreak by extending vaccination to all those with no prior history of vaccination.

Measles is a particular danger for children under one year who by virtue of their age have not yet been vaccinated. Susceptible adults are at risk of suffering more severe disease and the likelihood of complications.

Measles is an acute infectious viral disease characterised by general intoxication, fever, lesions of the mucous membranes of the eyes and respiratory system and is accompanied by a rash. Measles virus is transmitted from the patient via droplets through sneezing, coughing, talking, and even breathing.

Nearly 100 percent of unvaccinated people are sensitive to infection. Measles can be contracted by an unvaccinated person, even by entering a room where an infected person had been present a few hours previously. Measles is contagious 1-2 days before the 1st signs of illness appear and ceases to be contagious 5 days after the rash disappears. There is no specific treatment for measles. Therefore, it is essential to prevent its appearance by means of vaccination, employing the generally available live attenuated measles vaccine (included in the MMR triple vaccine).

--
