[7] USA (Florida)
Date: Thu 28 Mar 2013
Source: 7 News WSVN [edited]
http://www.wsvn.com/news/articles/local/21010221063363/1-so-fla-measles-case-reported/


On Thu 28 Mar 2013, Health Department officials have reported a confirmed case of measles in South Florida. The Florida Department of Health in Broward County reported that a 41-year-old woman had contracted the disease outside the United States. The department has notified facilities the patient may have visited, individuals who may have been exposed and Broward health care providers. Officials said the patient is doing well.

Measles is very rare in countries that are able to keep vaccination coverage high, but it is considered highly contagious. Measles virus spreads through the air by breathing, coughing or sneezing and can be transmitted from 4 days before the rash becomes visible to 4 days after it appears. Symptoms generally start showing up one to 2 weeks after a person is exposed to the virus and include a blotchy rash, fever, coughing, body aches and tiny white spots inside the mouth.

Anyone who has these symptoms should contact their health care provider. For more information, visit http://www.cdc.gov/measles/index.html.

